# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# .env.client.example — Client-side deployment (Transformers.js, in-browser)
#
# ✅ This deployment has NO backend server.
#    The agent runs entirely in the user's browser using Transformers.js.
#    There is no .env file to configure in this repo for client-side.
#
# All configuration for the client-side column lives in the FRONTEND repo
# (portfolio-frontend), not here.
# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

# ── What to set where (outside this file) ────────────────────────────────────
#
# VERCEL (portfolio-frontend repo → Settings → Environment Variables):
#
#   No backend URL needed — the frontend loads the model directly in the browser
#   via Transformers.js (WebGPU or WASM fallback).
#
#   Model: Qwen3-0.5B or Qwen3-1.8B (smaller variants that fit in browser memory)
#   The model is fetched from Hugging Face CDN on first load (~1 GB, cached).
#
#   Optional — if you add Hugging Face auth for gated models:
#   HF_TOKEN = hf_xxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxx
#              (Hugging Face → Settings → Access Tokens → New token → Read)
#
# NUXT FRONTEND:
#   The client column is self-contained — no API calls to this repo.
#   Inference runs in a Web Worker to avoid blocking the UI thread.
#
# ── Note on performance ───────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# Client-side inference is the comparison baseline: free, private (data never
# leaves the browser), but slowest — especially on devices without WebGPU.
# The frontend should detect WebGPU availability and show a warning if falling
# back to WASM (significantly slower).
